<p style="font-size: 18px; margin: 0px 0px 12px;">Automating backups in Data Protector is achieved by using Data Protector Backup Automation Blueprint OO content pack. The OO content pack allows integration and management of backups while provisioning infrastructure from Hybrid Cloud Manager (HCM) and any third party customer managed portal (CMP) using REST APIs. The OO workflow can be called out and backup can be placed and schedule as per the user input.</p><p style="font-size: 18px; margin: 0px 0px 12px;">Operations Orchestration (OO) is a system to create and use actions in structured sequences called flows. OO enables the orchestration on backup operations like provisioning clients, creating backup specification, scheduling backup, and restore the file and directory from the backup.</p><h2 style="font-family: MetricHPE_Medium; margin-top: 25px; margin-bottom: 6px; text-transform: none; padding-top: 0px; border-bottom: none; line-height: 25px; color: rgb(0, 115, 231) !important; font-size: 24px !important;"><span class="mw-headline" id="Prerequisites">Prerequisites</span></h2><p style="font-size: 18px; margin: 0px 0px 12px;">To automate backups using Data Protector Backup Automation Blueprint OO content pack, ensure the following:</p><ul style="margin-left: 18px; margin-top: 0px; padding: 0px 0px 0px 4px; margin-bottom: 0px; font-size: 18px;"><li>OO Central 10.80 and above is available.</li><li>Data Protector 10.00 and above installed on Linux server.</li></ul><h2 style="font-family: MetricHPE_Medium; margin-top: 25px; margin-bottom: 6px; text-transform: none; padding-top: 0px; border-bottom: none; line-height: 25px; color: rgb(0, 115, 231) !important; font-size: 24px !important;"><span class="mw-headline" id="Automate_backups_in_Data_Protector">Automate backups in Data Protector</span></h2><p style="font-size: 18px; margin: 0px 0px 12px;">To automate backups in Data Protector using OO, perform the following steps:</p><ol style="padding: 0px 0px 0px 4px; margin-top: 0px; margin-left: 20px; margin-bottom: 0.65em; font-size: 18px;"><li style="list-style-type: decimal; margin-left: 8px; margin-bottom: 0.65em; margin-top: 0.65em;">Install the Data Protector 10.00 and above in a Linux environment.<br>For example: Cell Manager server hostname: cell1centos.demo.local.</li><li style="list-style-type: decimal; margin-left: 8px; margin-bottom: 0.65em; margin-top: 0.65em;">Download backup automation scripts.<ol style="padding: 0px 0px 0px 4px; margin-top: 0px; margin-left: 20px; margin-bottom: 0.65em;"><li style="list-style-type: lower-alpha; margin-left: 4px; margin-bottom: 0.65em; margin-top: 0.65em;">Download and save the Backup_Automation_Scripts.zip from the Marketplace into a temp folder.</li><li style="list-style-type: lower-alpha; margin-left: 4px; margin-bottom: 0.65em; margin-top: 0.65em;">Extract the downloaded zip file and copy the contents into the&nbsp;<code style="font-size: 16px; font-family: MetricHPE_Medium; background-color: rgb(241, 242, 243); color: rgb(51, 51, 51) !important; padding: 2px 5px !important;">/opt/omni/lbin</code>&nbsp;folder of the Cell Manager server.</li></ol></li><li style="list-style-type: decimal; margin-left: 8px; margin-bottom: 0.65em; margin-top: 0.65em;">Extract the&nbsp;<span style="font-weight: 700;">Data_Protector_Automation_Blueprint_Scripts.zip</span>&nbsp;file in the&nbsp;<code style="font-size: 16px; font-family: MetricHPE_Medium; background-color: rgb(241, 242, 243); color: rgb(51, 51, 51) !important; padding: 2px 5px !important;">/opt/omni/lbin</code>&nbsp;folder. The contents of the zip file is extracted into a folder BAAS. This folder contains templates for file systems, Oracle database, and VM snapshot backup for DAILY, MONTHLY, and WEEKLY schedule.<br>For example:<pre style="padding: 1em; background-color: rgb(248, 249, 250); border-width: 1px; border-style: solid; border-color: rgb(234, 236, 240); margin-top: 4px; margin-bottom: 4px; font-family: Consolas, &quot;Courier New&quot;; line-height: 1.25em; overflow: auto; font-size: 14px !important;">cd /opt/omni/lbinBAAS
ls –l /opt/omni/lbin/BAAS
-rwxr-xr-x 1 root root 8344 Sep 26 16:01 BAAS_HCM.sh
-rw-r----- 1 root root  315 Sep 26 17:34 CLIENT_filesystem_DAILY
-rw-r----- 1 root root  318 Sep 26 17:35 CLIENT_filesystem_MONTHLY
-rw-r----- 1 root root  317 Sep 26 17:35 CLIENT_filesystem_WEEKLY
-rw-r--r-- 1 root root  388 Sep 26 10:55 CLIENT_snapshot_DAILY
-rw-r--r-- 1 root root  389 Sep 26 10:55 CLIENT_snapshot_MONTHLY
-rw-r--r-- 1 root root  389 Sep 26 10:55 CLIENT_snapshot_WEEKLY</pre></li><li style="list-style-type: decimal; margin-left: 8px; margin-bottom: 0.65em; margin-top: 0.65em;">4. Customize the scripts based your requirement. You can add a new template for a new component. To add a new template, complete the following steps:<ol style="padding: 0px 0px 0px 4px; margin-top: 0px; margin-left: 20px; margin-bottom: 0.65em;"><li style="list-style-type: lower-alpha; margin-left: 4px; margin-bottom: 0.65em; margin-top: 0.65em;">Create a copy of one of the DAILY, MONTHLY, or WEEKLY templates for the new component in the&nbsp;<code style="font-size: 16px; font-family: MetricHPE_Medium; background-color: rgb(241, 242, 243); color: rgb(51, 51, 51) !important; padding: 2px 5px !important;">/opt/omni/lbin/BAAS</code>&nbsp;folder.</li><li style="list-style-type: lower-alpha; margin-left: 4px; margin-bottom: 0.65em; margin-top: 0.65em;">Rename the template file in the&nbsp;<i>CLIENT_&lt;apptype&gt;_&lt;schedule&gt;</i>&nbsp;format.<br>Where &lt;<i>apptype</i>&gt; can be filesystem, lotus, oracle8, mailbox, mssql, mssps, sapdb, msvssw, sybase, sap, msese, vmware, e2010, mssharepoint, veagent, mysql, postgresql, idb, or db2 and &lt;<i>schedule</i>&gt; can be DAILY, MONTHLY, or WEEKLY.</li><li style="list-style-type: lower-alpha; margin-left: 4px; margin-bottom: 0.65em; margin-top: 0.65em;">Edit the newly created template to set the protection for DAILY, WEEKLY, and MONTHLY. For example, 26 days.</li><li style="list-style-type: lower-alpha; margin-left: 4px; margin-bottom: 0.65em; margin-top: 0.65em;">Edit the device name in template. Add the name of device in template.</li></ol></li><li style="list-style-type: decimal; margin-left: 8px; margin-bottom: 0.65em; margin-top: 0.65em;">Download and save the Backup Automation Data Protector OO content pack from the Marketplace in to a temp folder. Extract the contents of the zip file.</li><li style="list-style-type: decimal; margin-left: 8px; margin-bottom: 0.65em; margin-top: 0.65em;">Login to OO Studio.</li><li style="list-style-type: decimal; margin-left: 8px; margin-bottom: 0.65em; margin-top: 0.65em;">Import the&nbsp;<span style="font-weight: 700;">Backup-Automation-Data Protector-cp-1.0'<i>&nbsp;jar file from the extracted folder into the OO Studio. A new folder&nbsp;</i>OO Micro Focus Solutions</span>&nbsp;is created under the Dependencies pane in OO Studio.</li><li style="list-style-type: decimal; margin-left: 8px; margin-bottom: 0.65em; margin-top: 0.65em;">Select the&nbsp;<span style="font-weight: 700;">BAAS</span>&nbsp;folder from the Projects pane and expand to view the folder contents. The content pack for automating backups in Data Protector&nbsp;<span style="font-weight: 700;">Backup_Source</span>&nbsp;is available under the&nbsp;<span style="font-weight: 700;">Integrtions</span>&nbsp;subfolder.</li><li style="list-style-type: decimal; margin-left: 8px; margin-bottom: 0.65em; margin-top: 0.65em;">Run a content flow. For example,&nbsp;<span style="font-weight: 700;">Run DP Command</span>. Modify the properties as desired in the flow.</li><li style="list-style-type: decimal; margin-left: 8px; margin-bottom: 0.65em; margin-top: 0.65em;">Execute the OO flow. Open the Local Connections tab and click Play icon.</li><li style="list-style-type: decimal; margin-left: 8px; margin-bottom: 0.65em; margin-top: 0.65em;">Specify the following values to execute provisioning and creating the backup for various application type:<ul style="margin-left: 18px; margin-top: 0px; padding: 0px 0px 0px 4px; margin-bottom: 0px;"><li style="list-style-type: disc; margin-left: 6px; margin-bottom: 0.65em; margin-top: 0.65em;">Cell Manager name. For example: cell1centos.demo.local.</li><li style="list-style-type: disc; margin-left: 6px; margin-bottom: 0.65em; margin-top: 0.65em;">Cell Manager username and password.</li><li style="list-style-type: disc; margin-left: 6px; margin-bottom: 0.65em; margin-top: 0.65em;">Installation server hostname. For example: cell1centos.demo.local.</li><li style="list-style-type: disc; margin-left: 6px; margin-bottom: 0.65em; margin-top: 0.65em;">Client hostname. For example: cell1centos.demo.local.</li><li style="list-style-type: disc; margin-left: 6px; margin-bottom: 0.65em; margin-top: 0.65em;">Client username and password.</li><li style="list-style-type: disc; margin-left: 6px; margin-bottom: 0.65em; margin-top: 0.65em;">Application type, as specified in Step 4 (ii). For example, filesystem.</li><li style="list-style-type: disc; margin-left: 6px; margin-bottom: 0.65em; margin-top: 0.65em;">Schedule, as specified in Step 4 (iii). For example, DAILY.</li><li style="list-style-type: disc; margin-left: 6px; margin-bottom: 0.65em; margin-top: 0.65em;">Components list. For example, -cc A.10.20 –da A.10.20 –ma A.10.20.</li></ul></li><li style="list-style-type: decimal; margin-left: 8px; margin-bottom: 0.65em; margin-top: 0.65em;">Click&nbsp;<span style="font-weight: 700;">Continue</span>&nbsp;and monitor the logs.</li><li style="list-style-type: decimal; margin-left: 8px; margin-bottom: 0.65em; margin-top: 0.65em;">Integrate OO though REST API with any other third party CMP tool or HCM to manage the provisioning and decommissioning of backup through common portal.</li></ol>